@startuml paak_access_to_door_command_signal_flow
!theme plain
skinparam backgroundColor #FFFFFF
skinparam defaultFontName Arial
skinparam defaultFontSize 11
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam responseMessageBelowArrow true

title PAAK Access To Door Command Signal Flow\n(PAAK/TMU vehicle context -> BCM -> door control)

participant "PAAK / TMU /\nvehicle context inputs" as AccessCtx #F4F7FB
participant "BCM\nbody access owner" as BCM #E8F7E8
participant "Door modules /\nBody command bus" as Doors #FFF4CC
participant "Observers / panels" as Obs #E8F0FE

== Access Context Inputs ==

AccessCtx -> BCM : PAAK auth/proximity/state\nTMU service / remote climate\nvehicle drive state
BCM -> BCM : if manualMode == 0\nand driveState == 0\nand paakAuthLevel >= 1\nand paakProximityState >= 2\nand paakState >= 1\nthen doorControlCmd = 1
note right of BCM
Representative access inputs
- gPaakState / AuthLevel / ProximityState
- gTmuServiceMode / RemoteClimateReq
- gDriveState
end note

== Door Command Ownership ==

BCM -> BCM : childLockState =\n(manualMode == 0 and driveState > 0) ? 1 : 0
BCM -> Doors : frmDoorControlMsg\nDoorControlCmd / ChildLockCmd
BCM -> BCM : command trace for access and child lock
note right of BCM
Representative outputs
- frmDoorControlMsg
- DoorControlCmd
- ChildLockCmd
end note

== Downstream Visibility ==

Doors -> Obs : door actuator result /\nbody access readback

note over AccessCtx, Obs
Representative runtime chain
1. PAAK and vehicle context reach BCM
2. BCM determines whether access conditions allow door command
3. BCM publishes DoorControlCmd / ChildLockCmd
4. Door modules and observers reflect access-driven body behavior
end note

@enduml
